Generative AI for tracked/mod music?
text:
It seems to me like an AI that generates music based on modules would be a good thing.  Not only is there a dataset that's unimaginably huge, who wouldn't want to hear a stream of unique tracker music that never ends?
I think someone should look into this.  Is anyone already doing such a thing?

title: Too Connected to Fail
Tell HN: You need an efficent mouse setup with mapped mouse button actions
text:
The majority of my time "developing" is actually spent in a web browser skimming through documentation, googling for stuff, browsing through pages and going back and forth in history.

For about a decade now I've been using a series of mice with two mappable buttons on each side set up in the following way:

Left side: Forward and Back

Right side: Page Up and Page Down

I have found this to be incredibly effective. Bonus: It also works really well in VS Code, Spotify and other Electron-like apps.

You need a mouse with at least two buttons on each side. Advanced mice are called gaming mice nowadays. They come in all shapes. At the moment I'm using an old wired Razer Lancehead. Logitech has at least one current model with two mappable buttons on each side. Razer Viper 8KHz (sic) is another one.

My Experience with Bing
text:
Recently I used bing chat, and I have to say, I am impressed as hell.
Here's why. I write short stories, flash fiction. No, I am not some great writer, it's just a hobby thing. I was writing a piece about an older person, like me, overhearing a conversation of some young people on an airplane, and a pretentious sounding young man bragging about having kiss some young woman. I asked bing, how would a young person describe kissing a young woman. It refused to do so. At first I was taken aback
